01:05:22.480 --> 01:05:28.720
He was a leading expert in plasma physics. The work Nuno was conducting at MIT was attempting to

01:05:28.720 --> 01:05:31.360
solve the hardest problems in nuclear fusion.

01:05:34.560 --> 01:05:38.800
Problems that would unlock our capabilities in clean fusion power,

01:05:38.800 --> 01:05:42.240
potentially solving the world's energy crisis forever.

01:05:43.040 --> 01:05:47.680
For those unaware, nuclear fusion would be the ultimate clean energy dream,

01:05:47.680 --> 01:05:51.360
bringing the sun to the earth and powering our whole society.

01:05:51.360 --> 01:05:55.520
No fossil fuel pollution or Chernobyl-style meltdown necessary.

01:05:55.520 --> 01:06:00.640
Wielding fusion power would dramatically reduce the human need for fossil fuels.

01:06:00.640 --> 01:06:06.560
And with that, we might be able to avoid a lot of the geopolitical escapades we're seeing happening today.

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:14.000
But there's one great challenge. Plasma is a chaotic soup of charged ionized gas,

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:20.400
which behaves in wildly unpredictable ways. To contain it, and to force the atoms to fuse,

01:06:20.400 --> 01:06:27.280
demands a special magnetic field, one which binds the plasma up into just the right geometry,

01:06:27.280 --> 01:06:33.120
and under just enough pressure to force the atoms to merge, despite the immense repulsive force

01:06:33.120 --> 01:06:38.400
between them. There are many challenges to nuclear fusion, but perhaps the greatest

01:06:38.400 --> 01:06:45.040
is the problem of the containment field. It is no simple task, but it's where Nuno Lurero excelled.

01:06:45.040 --> 01:06:50.560
His research was especially focused on one of the greatest challenges in plasma containment fields,

01:06:51.120 --> 01:06:59.040
magnetic reconnection. Consider the loops of plasma we see on the sun. Plasma gets trapped

01:06:59.040 --> 01:07:05.440
in arcs of opposite magnetic force. It usually gets trapped in tubes of electromagnetic energy,

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:12.400
hot particles rising out of the sun's surface and falling back in. Sometimes, like a rubber band

01:07:12.400 --> 01:07:18.960
that's been stretched too much, it snaps. The field lines break. All the energy stored in the field

01:07:18.960 --> 01:07:26.000
bursts out as the particles heat up and accelerate out. Then the field reconnects. This process causes

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:33.040
solar flares and coronal mass ejections, the kind of events that could one day fry our entire grid

01:07:33.040 --> 01:07:39.120
with an electromagnetic pulse, or EMP. Nuno was a real blue sky researcher,

01:07:39.120 --> 01:07:42.480
studying the phenomenon of magnetic reconnection itself.

01:07:45.040 --> 01:07:51.920
But his work had extremely practical applications, because just as reconnection causes flares from the sun,

01:07:52.480 --> 01:07:59.200
it's also a major factor in our attempts to bring the sun's power down to Earth, and do so in the form of

01:07:59.200 --> 01:08:07.200
real nuclear fusion. Giant donut-shaped tokamak reactors use powerful magnets to contain superheated plasma,

01:08:07.200 --> 01:08:13.760
and magnetic reconnection is one of the greatest obstacles to sustained nuclear fusion. Just like plasma

01:08:13.760 --> 01:08:20.960
ejections from the sun, often with fusion, a leak gets created, leading to rapid cooling and pressure loss.

01:08:20.960 --> 01:08:27.360
This effectively stops the fusion process dead in its tracks. Nuno Lurero was one of the world's

01:08:27.360 --> 01:08:34.800
experts in understanding the intricacies of exactly how and why these magnetic reconnection leaks happen.

01:08:34.800 --> 01:08:41.200
We don't know if Nuno came close to solving the problem of magnetic field line breaks. But we do know

01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:48.080
he was probably as close as anybody. And at 47 years old, it's safe to say he had many impressive

01:08:48.080 --> 01:08:55.520
decades of discovery and invention ahead of him. Except on December 15th, Dr. Nuno Lurero was gunned down

01:08:55.520 --> 01:08:57.920
inside his Brookline, Massachusetts home.

01:09:01.200 --> 01:09:07.200
Nuno Lurero was a husband, a father, an award-winning scientist, and expert in his field.

01:09:07.200 --> 01:09:13.680
He was shot in the foyer of his apartment while his wife, mother, and daughters played a card game inside.

01:09:14.240 --> 01:09:19.760
The only other person who saw his killer was his 12-year-old daughter, who first answered the door

01:09:19.760 --> 01:09:25.440
for what she thought was a delivery man. Later, authorities would report that Claudio Manuel

01:09:25.440 --> 01:09:31.680
Neves Valente, the Portuguese national and top suspect in the shooting at Brown University that

01:09:31.680 --> 01:09:39.040
had occurred just two days prior, was likely also Nuno's killer. In some ways, this seemed very plausible.

01:09:39.040 --> 01:09:45.920
Nuno and Claudio had both studied physics together 20 years ago at Portugal's Instituto Superior

01:09:45.920 --> 01:09:51.760
Tecnico. Physics programs are tight-knit. They're also highly competitive. The men certainly knew each

01:09:51.760 --> 01:09:58.080
other and were part of the same graduating class. But Nuno was actually an average student in undergrad,

01:09:58.080 --> 01:10:03.920
whereas Claudio was tied with another student for top of his class. Claudio had his heart set on

01:10:03.920 --> 01:10:09.840
MIT for graduate school. But as a surprise to everyone, he didn't score very well on his graduate

01:10:09.840 --> 01:10:16.400
school admissions test, making MIT a reach. He ultimately didn't get in. Claudio Valente was

01:10:16.400 --> 01:10:22.640
accepted to Brown University instead, but felt let down by a lack of academic rigor in their physics

01:10:22.640 --> 01:10:28.960
program, insisting his classes were too easy, covering material he'd already learned in undergrad.

01:10:28.960 --> 01:10:33.600
Claudio was described as egotistical and combative by his classmates at Brown.

01:10:33.600 --> 01:10:39.360
He only made it a year into the program before taking a leave of absence. Eventually, he dropped

01:10:39.360 --> 01:10:45.840
out of the program entirely and returned to Portugal. That year, he posted a disgruntled note online.

01:10:45.840 --> 01:10:51.360
Happy now? And some now believe Valente harbored deep resentment for his former classmate,

01:10:51.360 --> 01:10:55.760
Nuno Larreiro, whose massive success would have been assault in the wound.

01:10:55.760 --> 01:11:06.560
Back in Portugal, tail between his legs, Valente worked at an internet company called SAPO, or SAPO.

01:11:06.560 --> 01:11:12.720
His colleagues described him as highly competent and rigorous, polite, but aloof. His closest friend

01:11:12.720 --> 01:11:19.200
at work, Sergio Bastos, who worked with him for seven years, insisted Valente was an extraordinary

01:11:19.200 --> 01:11:24.800
professional. He did things that few people were capable of doing, but admitted that he was very

01:11:24.800 --> 01:11:29.920
lonely. I think one of the great regrets he had was that he couldn't create his own family,

01:11:29.920 --> 01:11:36.240
Mr. Bastos said. He had few social skills, and I don't think he had any girlfriends in the years we

01:11:36.240 --> 01:11:44.480
worked together. One day in 2013, Valente reported to work. He declared it would be his last day.

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:51.360
He turned in his laptop, and he was never seen again.

01:11:51.360 --> 01:11:56.960
Bastos tried in vain to reach out, but at this point, no one from Valente's former life could make

01:11:56.960 --> 01:12:04.480
contact, including his own family. In 2017, Valente applied for and was awarded a visa to the United

01:12:04.480 --> 01:12:10.080
States. He settled in Miami, Florida, where authorities are still trying to piece together

01:12:10.080 --> 01:12:15.280
how exactly he spent his time. What we do know is that for the past three years,

01:12:15.280 --> 01:12:20.960
Valente rented a storage unit in Salem, New Hampshire, and returned to Providence numerous

01:12:20.960 --> 01:12:28.560
times to conduct surveillance on the Brown campus. Investigators eventually traced Valente to Boston

01:12:28.560 --> 01:12:36.880
as early as November 17, 2025. By late November, he had checked into a Boston hotel and began making

01:12:36.880 --> 01:12:44.240
repeated trips to Providence. A janitor at Brown saw a masked man matching Valente's description

01:12:44.240 --> 01:12:51.760
inside the Barris and Hawley Engineering Building on November 28 and again on December 1. On December

01:12:51.760 --> 01:12:58.320
1, Valente rented a blue-gray Nissan Sentra with Florida plates. That car was seen repeatedly around

01:12:58.320 --> 01:13:05.200
Brown between December 1 and December 12. The picture was clear. This was pre-operational reconnaissance.

01:13:05.200 --> 01:13:14.560
Valente executed his plan on Saturday, December 13, 2025. He barged into an open lecture hall in the

01:13:14.560 --> 01:13:20.320
Barris and Hawley Building, the home of the physics department where students were taking final exams

01:13:20.320 --> 01:13:28.320
before their winter holiday. Around 4 p.m., Valente opened fire with a 9mm pistol, killing two students

01:13:28.320 --> 01:13:35.920
and injuring nine others. Valente would leave a confessional video behind. It was filmed in his

01:13:35.920 --> 01:13:42.640
storage unit as a massive federal and state manhunt was still underway. He confessed that he had spent

01:13:42.640 --> 01:13:49.280
six semesters planning his attack at Brown. After the shooting on December 13, Valente successfully

01:13:49.280 --> 01:13:55.360
evaded law enforcement for two full days, using a burner phone with a European SIM card, as well as

01:13:55.360 --> 01:14:01.280
swapping out credit cards and the license plate on his rental car, his identity remained a mystery.

01:14:01.280 --> 01:14:06.880
Valente might have gotten away with his crimes, except for the fact that he had one more act of

01:14:06.880 --> 01:14:12.960
violence planned. At some point between Saturday and Sunday, Valente drove back to Boston. And on

01:14:12.960 --> 01:14:20.080
Monday, December 15, Valente spent the day pacing around Commonwealth Avenue. Maybe Valente saw

01:14:20.080 --> 01:14:27.440
Lurero as a representation of everything he couldn't amount to, a successful academic, a family man,

01:14:27.440 --> 01:14:34.160
a leader in his field of physics, a successful emigrant to America. This may have just been a

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:40.400
modern physics-based rendition of an age-old Shakespearean play. But still, there's something

01:14:40.400 --> 01:14:46.800
both strangely calculated and apprehensive about Claudio Valente's actions leading up to his confrontation

01:14:46.800 --> 01:14:56.320
with Lurero. Authorities have much more information about Valente's whereabouts in Providence prior to

01:14:56.320 --> 01:15:03.200
his Brown shooting. After that, he kind of goes dark. And for the rest of Saturday and all of Sunday,

01:15:03.200 --> 01:15:10.640
Valente seems to drop off the map. On Monday, December 15, Providence police were still circulating

01:15:10.640 --> 01:15:16.640
surveillance clips from Brown. They were also still interviewing survivors. The shooter had not been

01:15:16.640 --> 01:15:24.320
identified. That same evening, at about 8.30 p.m., Lurero was shot at his home on Gibb Street in

01:15:24.320 --> 01:15:31.200
Brookline, Massachusetts. Earlier that day, the familiar Nissan made its first appearance parked on

01:15:31.200 --> 01:15:39.440
Babcock Street around 8 a.m., five or six blocks from Lurero's home. Then, starting around 1.20 p.m.,

01:15:39.440 --> 01:15:45.600
police say security cameras recorded a masked person at different points along Commonwealth Avenue.

01:15:46.480 --> 01:15:53.760
Nuno reportedly got home from overseeing PhD-qualifying exams at MIT that day around 6 p.m.

01:15:53.760 --> 01:16:01.040
At 8.23 p.m., a camera records the suspect, now masked and wearing a vest over his darker clothing.

01:16:01.040 --> 01:16:07.520
At 8.30 p.m., the doorbell to Lurero's apartment rings repeatedly. His youngest daughter opens the front

01:16:07.520 --> 01:16:16.000
door and peeks into the foyer. She sees through the glass a man standing inside of the building,

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:21.120
but on the other side of the foyer door. Her description of the man's clothing is mostly in

01:16:21.120 --> 01:16:27.040
line with the footage revealed, but she adds that the yellow vest he wore had some gray stripes.

01:16:27.040 --> 01:16:32.400
There are a few discrepancies in her observations compared to the footage seen of the suspect that

01:16:32.400 --> 01:16:39.040
day. She even describes the shooter as having short facial hair, which suggests that he's not wearing

01:16:39.040 --> 01:16:45.920
a mask. And according to her, he's also wearing a winter hat and carrying a cardboard package about

01:16:45.920 --> 01:16:51.600
the size of a dictionary. She thinks he's a delivery man because the package has a barcode on it.

01:16:51.600 --> 01:16:57.280
Lurero's daughter returns to the living room as Nuno replaces her at the front door to deal with the

01:16:57.280 --> 01:17:05.760
visitor. The whole family hears gunshots and rushes to Lurero, who is wounded in the upper left chest,

01:17:05.760 --> 01:17:11.680
upper abdomen, right thigh, and has a graze wound through his left thigh. The daughter sees the

01:17:11.680 --> 01:17:19.040
shooter run to a blue or gray car parked across the street. At 8.35 p.m., the cameras outside a Boston

01:17:19.040 --> 01:17:25.520
University Police Department record a Nissan operated by someone wearing a HiVise vest.

01:17:25.520 --> 01:17:29.680
Minutes later, another camera records the vehicle heading out of the city.

01:17:29.680 --> 01:17:35.600
If we're to believe that the shooter was Valente, it seems clear that once Lurero was shot,

01:17:35.600 --> 01:17:42.080
he immediately went into hiding. He switched the rental car's plates to an unregistered plate from Maine,

01:17:42.080 --> 01:17:47.440
then drove to his storage facility in New Hampshire. Investigators said Valente entered that

01:17:47.440 --> 01:17:53.360
facility about an hour after the Brookline shooting. The Department of Justice transcript of the videos

01:17:53.360 --> 01:17:59.840
that Valente later recorded in that storage unit adds a very grim layer to the story. In these

01:17:59.840 --> 01:18:06.320
recordings, Valente said he had planned the Brown attack for a long time. The language Valente uses

01:18:06.320 --> 01:18:12.560
implies that both of the attacks were intentional, but it still leaves the reason for targeting Lurero

01:18:12.560 --> 01:18:19.040
maddeningly vague. Yes, the two men had studied in the same university in the 1990s, but there's no

01:18:19.040 --> 01:18:25.440
evidence of a recent dispute, direct contact, or a concrete grievance tied to the Brookline attack.

01:18:26.160 --> 01:18:32.560
A second anomaly is the mismatch between planning and execution. Valente seems to have surveilled

01:18:32.560 --> 01:18:38.560
Brown repeatedly. He would return constantly to the same building. He rented both a car and storage unit

01:18:38.560 --> 01:18:45.200
in advance. Yet his own post-crime confession depicts the actual Brown shooting as totally botched.

01:18:45.200 --> 01:18:50.880
He said he never wanted to do it in an auditorium. He even suggested that people could have escaped

01:18:50.880 --> 01:18:57.120
via an emergency exit. He also complained about his eye injury and described the whole thing as,

01:18:57.120 --> 01:19:03.200
quote, a little incompetent. A third anomaly is the timeline gap between the two attacks.

01:19:03.200 --> 01:19:09.760
Where exactly was Valente in the roughly 48 hours before Lurero was shot? Where was he staying?

01:19:09.760 --> 01:19:16.080
How did he locate Lurero? How could he even be sure Lurero was home? Nuno had only just returned

01:19:16.080 --> 01:19:22.800
from a trip to DC. Was he being tracked somehow? Valente's videos hint that the second slaying

01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:28.720
was also intentional, but not how far back the planning went. Detectives arrived on the scene to

01:19:28.720 --> 01:19:35.280
find Lurero distressed but consciously alert. As he's transported to the hospital, one paramedic

01:19:35.280 --> 01:19:41.760
says he doesn't say anything. She believes he was in shock. He answers questions by shaking his head.

01:19:41.760 --> 01:19:48.080
But at the hospital, he was able to provide his name and information. If Lurero had recognized his

01:19:48.080 --> 01:19:54.560
possibly unmasked killer as his former classmate, would he have said anything? Tragically,

01:19:54.560 --> 01:20:01.120
Nuno Lurero went into surgery that evening, but did not survive. He was pronounced dead the following

01:20:01.120 --> 01:20:05.920
morning. In the days that followed, they spoke to the MIT professor's family and colleagues,

01:20:05.920 --> 01:20:10.560
and they said that there was no threat present, and they still have no motive.

01:20:10.560 --> 01:20:16.320
Everything about this case is shocking, but particularly Valente's combination of caution

01:20:16.320 --> 01:20:22.480
and sloppiness. He went to great efforts and lengths in Providence to wipe any trace of his movements,

01:20:22.480 --> 01:20:28.800
keep his identity hidden. But then he arrives in Boston and paces back and forth in public locations

01:20:28.800 --> 01:20:34.000
that would obviously have security cameras. It almost seems as if he was having cold feet.

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:39.120
Or maybe he was awaiting instruction. Subliminal or conscious instruction.

01:20:41.600 --> 01:20:48.640
As we've covered on this show, the horrifying ability to program assassins is remarkably easy,

01:20:48.640 --> 01:20:54.160
and it's been demonstrated by governments globally and employed to take out targets at the highest

01:20:54.160 --> 01:21:00.160
level. What remains unresolved is why Lurero was chosen, what exactly happened in the two days

01:21:00.160 --> 01:21:05.760
between the Brown massacre and the Brookline attack, and whether Lurero had been a long-standing target

01:21:05.760 --> 01:21:11.920
or simply became one after the Brown shooting was already underway. What we do know is that Nuno Lurero's

01:21:11.920 --> 01:21:18.400
loss is devastating. He wasn't just the head of MIT's Plasma Science and Fusion Center. Nuno was

01:21:18.400 --> 01:21:24.560
still an active professor, training the next generation of top scientific minds to push us

01:21:24.560 --> 01:21:31.040
farther in harnessing the power of our sun and creating clean energy on Earth. He was twice awarded

01:21:31.040 --> 01:21:37.360
the MIT Department of Nuclear Science and Engineering Outstanding Professor Award. He was given this for the

01:21:37.360 --> 01:21:45.040
beloved courses that he taught, both Intro to Plasma Physics and MHD Theory of Fusion Systems. MHD,

01:21:45.040 --> 01:21:52.080
or magnetohydrodynamics, also could have just as sensitive implications as nuclear fusion. It's the

01:21:52.080 --> 01:21:58.080
less focused on aspect of Lurero's work. And these are called the magnetohydrodynamic equations. They're

01:21:58.080 --> 01:22:04.880
hydrodynamics, but now there's a magnetic field, so you refer to this as magnetohydrodynamics. Some believe

01:22:04.880 --> 01:22:11.200
that it could lead to a whole new paradigm in flight and propulsion. The point is, an attack on Nuno was

01:22:11.200 --> 01:22:17.200
an attack on the future of science. There's no other way to say it. To put it simply, Nuno was the tip

01:22:17.200 --> 01:22:24.880
of the spear on sustained, clean, widespread nuclear fusion energy. Could that be why someone wanted him dead?

01:22:24.880 --> 01:22:34.000
This brings us to a strange coincidence we have to bring up when discussing Nuno Lurero's murder.

01:22:34.000 --> 01:22:39.280
Breaking news out of Brookline, an MIT professor shot and killed. He was shot several times in the foyer

01:22:39.280 --> 01:22:44.880
of his Brookline home. Just two days after Nuno's death, one of the top privately funded fusion

01:22:44.880 --> 01:22:52.880
companies, TAE Technologies, announced a massive merger with a surprising publicly traded company. TAE would

01:22:52.880 --> 01:22:58.800
merge with none other than Trump Media and Technology Group, the company behind Trump's social media

01:22:58.800 --> 01:23:06.800
platform Truth Social. The deal was announced on December 18th, 2025. Lurero died on December 16th.

01:23:06.800 --> 01:23:12.560
The announcement didn't coincide with any decisive technical breakthroughs. Nonetheless, this combined

01:23:12.560 --> 01:23:19.760
entity was suddenly valued at around $6 billion. TAE is a private long-running experimental company.

01:23:19.760 --> 01:23:25.360
Their mission is to build aneutronic fusion reactors using hydrogen boron fuel to make

01:23:25.360 --> 01:23:31.200
commercial nuclear energy. But just like all fusion enterprises so far, they have yet to produce net

01:23:31.200 --> 01:23:36.880
energy or commercial power. TAE is still pre-revenue and pre-product in its core mission.

01:23:37.440 --> 01:23:42.960
So why is any of this relevant? Well, there are a few key competitors in the race with TAE to produce

01:23:42.960 --> 01:23:48.960
commercial nuclear power. One of their biggest competitors is a company called Commonwealth Fusion Systems.

01:23:48.960 --> 01:23:54.800
Commonwealth Fusion Systems is a company that emerged directly from the Massachusetts Institute

01:23:54.800 --> 01:24:01.680
of Technology. Its founders built their work on decades of MIT's institutional research. The MIT

01:24:01.680 --> 01:24:07.760
Plasma Science Infusion Center collaborates closely with the company and contributes fundamental plasma

01:24:07.760 --> 01:24:13.920
physics essential to its reactor design. And Nuno Lurero was the director of the Plasma Science

01:24:13.920 --> 01:24:19.840
Science Infusion Center at the time of his death. So the head of research that directly supports

01:24:19.840 --> 01:24:25.280
Commonwealth's aim of stable nuclear energy was assassinated on his doorstep.

01:24:25.280 --> 01:24:29.760
We want to give you some context on exactly where this happened. The shooting was on Gibb Street in

01:24:29.760 --> 01:24:30.240
Brooklyn.

01:24:30.240 --> 01:24:32.320
A shot and killed at his Brooklyn Hall.

01:24:32.320 --> 01:24:35.520
I'm walking around. I got children in the playground right around the corner.

01:24:35.520 --> 01:24:39.280
Authorities say the Portuguese professor died at a hospital this morning.

01:24:39.280 --> 01:24:45.520
And two days later, one of Commonwealth's biggest competitors announces a merger with a sitting

01:24:45.520 --> 01:24:51.600
president's publicly traded company. Does that mean anything? I'm not entirely sure,

01:24:51.600 --> 01:24:57.200
and I genuinely don't want to insinuate anything. But I also think it's dogmatic and unreasonable to

01:24:57.200 --> 01:25:03.680
say that the timing isn't odd. Again, there are reasonable explanations for this merger. Most analysts

01:25:03.680 --> 01:25:08.640
say that any fusion company will need the support of the federal government to bring this nascent,

01:25:08.640 --> 01:25:14.960
unproven, and extremely costly technology out of the laboratories and onto the power grid. It's simply

01:25:14.960 --> 01:25:20.640
too cost and infrastructure intensive and would involve a complete overhaul of our current grid

01:25:20.640 --> 01:25:26.560
system. There are other power players in oil and gas who have an interest in TAE. A great example is

01:25:26.560 --> 01:25:33.440
Chevron. Ultimately, the question remains, what lengths would the power players in energy go to shore up

01:25:33.440 --> 01:25:39.840
their survival and dominance. There's clearly a race to control the technology that could determine

01:25:39.840 --> 01:25:46.000
the future of energy, aerospace, and intelligence in our modern world. And Nuno Lurero's research was

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:50.560
at the heart of it. I think on any given day, it's tempting to go for the low-hanging fruit,

01:25:50.560 --> 01:25:53.600
be a little more ambitious, and tackle the really hard problems.

01:25:55.920 --> 01:26:02.160
It would hardly be the first time scientific talent tied to strategic technology seemed to attract

01:26:02.160 --> 01:26:09.440
a shadow of danger. In the heart of the Cold War, as America raced to build Reagan's Star Wars missile

01:26:09.440 --> 01:26:14.480
shield, something deeply sinister began happening to the scientists building it.

01:26:14.480 --> 01:26:19.120
It's a story so rich and intriguing that if it were fiction, it would likely be a bestseller,

01:26:19.120 --> 01:26:24.080
because all of the dead, almost two dozen to date, worked in Western Europe's defense industry.

01:26:26.080 --> 01:26:31.120
You might not know that Star Wars, also known as the Strategic Defense Initiative,

01:26:31.120 --> 01:26:37.280
was actually a joint effort between the United States and some of its key allies, like Great Britain.

01:26:37.280 --> 01:26:46.160
Between 1982 and 1990, 25 engineers and computer scientists, all working for GEC Marconi,

01:26:46.160 --> 01:26:52.000
on some of Britain's most classified defense projects, all died, one after another.

01:26:52.560 --> 01:26:58.400
I call upon the scientific community in our country, those who gave us nuclear weapons,

01:26:58.400 --> 01:27:02.160
to turn their great talents now to the cause of mankind and world peace.

01:27:04.480 --> 01:27:12.640
And each case was so bizarre. They consistently defied rational explanation. A 24-year-old jumped from a

01:27:12.640 --> 01:27:20.400
suspension bridge. His body was then found with mysterious needle puncture wounds in it. A 26-year-old

